TY  - JOUR
TI  - Special issue: Receptions of Pausanias: From Winckelmann to Frazer Introduction
AU  - Elsner, J
T2  - CLASSICAL RECEPTIONS JOURNAL
AB  - This volume focuses on the way the creative reading of Pausanias has been pivotal to the formation of new academic disciplines, especially in German and British writing in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries. From Winckelmann to Frazer, it charts the significance of deep engagements with Pausanias in the formation of art history, archaeology and anthropology, as well as the Picturesque and certain forms of Romanticism. The introduction traces how engagements with fantasies of Pausanias the man (learned professor, dull reporter, duplicitous Semite) have been crucial for the inflections of his reception over more than 200 years, and how the ancient text's own fight between persistent selectivity and a totalizing aspiration for encapsulating 'all things Greek' is itself key to the various struggles in reception between excerpted and totalizing readings.
