TY  - JOUR
TI  - Are highly accurate models of agency in bone breaking the result of misuse of machine learning methods?
AU  - Moclán, A
AU  - Domínguez-Rodrigo, M
T2  - JOURNAL OF ARCHAEOLOGICAL SCIENCE-REPORTS
AB  - Machine learning (ML) methods constitute a major advance in analytical archaeology and taphonomy. Their adoption by anthropologists, usually with limited training in data analysis, has recently raised some concerns about their correct use. Here, we test some of the main objections made regarding the standard use of ML algorithms on categorical taphonomic data sets, more specifically on the issue of agency in bone breaking analysis. We show that the correct use of ML generates models that are accurate because of their data properties, and not because of methodological biasing during training and testing. We also show alternative tools, like ensemble learning, that allows to increase the confidence of accurate models used for differentiating agency in bone breaking. The present work shows how experimental hammerstone-broken long bones and carnivore-broken long bones can be correctly classified with a moderate (>70 %) to high degree (>80 %) of accuracy by several ML methods. The results reinforce the confidence with which ML is being applied in Anthropology, and underscore the great improvement of their use for the analytical study of bone breaking in taphonomy.
